{"cursor":"15281","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n 'Colonies in antiquity' were city-states founded from a mother-\ncity—its \"metropolis\" see Metropolis for etymology —, not\nfrom a territory-at-large. Bonds between a colony and its metropolis remained\noften close, and took specific forms. However,\nunlike in the period of European colonialism during the early and late modern\nera, ancient colonies were usually sovereign and self-governing from their\ninception.\n","linknr":709,"url":"Colonies_in_antiquity","recorded":1362572584,"links":41,"instances":["sicily","roman"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Colonies in antiquity|","Greek colonization|","History of colonialism","Roman law","Foreign relations of Ancient Rome","Ancient Greece","Hellenistic generals"],"headings":["Egyptian colony","Phoenician colonies","Greek colonies","Roman colonies","Notes","See also","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f4/AntikeGriechen1.jpg/350px-AntikeGriechen1.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Ancient_colonies.PNG/300px-Ancient_colonies.PNG","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/Ancient_Greek_Colonies_of_N_Black_Sea.png/250px-Ancient_Greek_Colonies_of_N_Black_Sea.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/48/Folder_Hexagonal_Icon.svg/16px-Folder_Hexagonal_Icon.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fd/Portal-puzzle.svg/16px-Portal-puzzle.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/People_icon.svg/16px-People_icon.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediaw